VALUES
(43, 9, 22, 42, 6, 22, 22, 'put out of the synagogue', 'Fear of Exclusion for Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of being cast out for faith. Both passages emphasize the consequences of confessing belief in Christ, leading to separation from community.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 22, 19, 27, 1, 2, 'feared the Jews', 'Fear of the Wicked', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear in the face of opposition. In John 9:22, the parents'' fear of the Jews contrasts with the confidence expressed in Psalms 27:1-2, where the Lord is portrayed as a source of strength against enemies.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 22, 20, 29, 25, 25, 'feared the Jews', 'Fear and Trust in God', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in both passages. John 9:22 illustrates the fear of man leading to a denial of truth, while Proverbs 29:25 contrasts this by emphasizing trust in the Lord as a source of safety.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 22, 23, 51, 7, 7, NULL, 'Fear of Reproach', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in both passages. John 9:22 discusses the fear of being put out of the synagogue, while Isaiah 51:7 encourages not to fear the reproach of men.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 22, 23, 57, 11, 11, 'feared the Jews', 'Fear and Confession Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear influencing confession. In John 9:22, the parents'' fear of being put out of the synagogue leads them to withhold their acknowledgment of Christ, while Isaiah 57:11 questions the fear that leads to dishonesty and forgetting God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 23, 43, 9, 21, 21, 'he is of age; ask him', 'Parental Testimony on Blind Man', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''he is of age; ask him,'' indicating that the parents defer to their son regarding his healing. This connection highlights their acknowledgment of his maturity and ability to speak for himself.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 24, 6, 7, 19, 19, 'give God the praise', 'Confession and Giving Glory', 'Both passages emphasize the act of giving glory to God and making confession. In John, the blind man is urged to praise God, while in Joshua, Achan is instructed to confess and give glory to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 24, 43, 9, 16, 16, 'this man is a sinner', 'Debate on Jesus'' Sinfulness', 'Both passages emphasize the division among the Pharisees regarding Jesus'' nature. In John 9:16, some question how a sinner can perform miracles, while in John 9:24, they insist that Jesus is a sinner, highlighting the ongoing conflict over his identity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 24, 43, 8, 49, 49, 'give God the praise', 'Honor and Dishonor Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of honor and dishonor. In John 9:24, the blind man is pressured to dishonor Jesus by labeling Him a sinner, while in John 8:49, Jesus asserts that He honors the Father despite being dishonored by others.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 24, 9, 6, 5, 9, 'Give God the praise', 'Glorifying God in Adversity', 'Both passages emphasize the act of giving glory to God in the face of suffering or challenge. In John 9:24, the blind man is urged to praise God despite accusations against Jesus, while in 1 Samuel 6:5, the Philistines are instructed to give glory to God to alleviate their afflictions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 24, 19, 50, 14, 15, 'Give God the praise', 'Praise and Thanksgiving Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of glorifying God in both passages. John 9:24 emphasizes giving praise to God, while Psalms 50:14-15 encourages offering thanksgiving and glorifying Him in times of trouble.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 24, 23, 66, 5, 5, 'Give God the praise', 'Praise and Shame Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of glorifying God amidst opposition. Both passages reflect the tension between those who honor God and those who reject His messengers, leading to shame for the latter.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 24, 41, 15, 27, 27, 'Give God the praise', 'Theme of Judgment and Suffering', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment faced by individuals in both passages. The blind man is judged by others for his healing, while the thieves are judged and crucified alongside Jesus, emphasizing societal condemnation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 25, 62, 5, 10, 10, 'now I see', 'Witness of Transformation', 'This connection highlights the theme of personal testimony and belief. In John 9:25, the man''s transformation from blindness to sight serves as a witness to the power of faith, paralleling 1 John 5:10, which emphasizes the internal witness of belief in the Son of God.', 'theme', 0.349, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 25, 43, 5, 11, 11, NULL, 'Healing and Transformation', 'Both passages emphasize a significant transformation in the individuals'' lives. The blind man in John 9:25 experiences physical sight, while the man in John 5:11 is made whole, highlighting the theme of healing and restoration.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 25, 43, 9, 30, 30, 'whereas I was blind, now I see', 'Connection of Blindness and Sight', 'Both passages emphasize the transformation from blindness to sight. The man acknowledges his previous blindness and the miracle of gaining sight, highlighting the significance of this change.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 27, 42, 22, 67, 67, 'ye did not hear', 'Questioning Belief in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of questioning when belief is absent. The speaker in each verse expresses frustration over the audience''s unwillingness to hear or believe the truth.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 27, 43, 9, 10, 15, 'I have told you already', 'Blind Man''s Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize the blind man''s experience of receiving sight and his subsequent testimony. In John 9:27, he challenges the Pharisees about their refusal to listen to his account of how he was healed.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 28, 45, 2, 17, 17, 'Moses’ disciples', 'Discipleship and Law Observance', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of discipleship and reliance on the law. In John, the revilers claim allegiance to Moses, while in Romans, the focus is on being called a Jew and resting in the law.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 28, 23, 51, 7, 7, 'reviled him', 'Reproach and Reviling Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of reviling and reproach faced by the faithful. John 9:28 mentions reviling in the context of discipleship, while Isaiah 51:7 encourages not to fear reproach from men.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 28, 40, 5, 11, 11, NULL, 'Reviling and Persecution Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of being reviled and persecuted for one''s beliefs. In John 9:28, the reviling occurs against the disciple of Jesus, while Matthew 5:11 speaks of being blessed when reviled for His sake.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 28, 40, 27, 39, 39, 'reviled him', 'Reviling and Mockery', 'Both passages emphasize the act of reviling, where individuals express scorn towards others. In John 9:28, the reviling is directed at the disciple of Jesus, while in Matthew 27:39, it is directed at Jesus himself.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 28, 43, 5, 45, 47, 'Moses’ disciples', 'Connection Between Moses and Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Moses and the belief in Jesus. In John 9:28, the revilers claim to be disciples of Moses, while John 5:45-47 highlights that trusting in Moses should lead to belief in Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 28, 43, 7, 19, 19, 'Moses’ disciples', 'Connection Between Moses and Law', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Moses and the law. In John 9:28, the claim of being ''Moses’ disciples'' contrasts with the failure to uphold the law mentioned in John 7:19.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 28, 44, 6, 11, 14, 'Moses’ disciples', 'Connection of Discipleship and Blasphemy', 'Both passages emphasize the conflict between Jesus'' followers and those loyal to Moses. In John 9:28, the revilers claim to be Moses'' disciples, while in Acts 6:11-14, Stephen is accused of speaking against Moses, highlighting the tension between the two groups.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 29, 43, 8, 14, 14, 'we know not from whence he is', 'Knowledge of Origin', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowledge regarding one''s origin. In John 9:29, the speakers claim ignorance about Jesus'' origins, while in John 8:14, Jesus asserts that he knows whence he came.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 29, 4, 12, 2, 7, NULL, 'Authority of God''s Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of God''s chosen messenger. In John 9:29, the speakers question the legitimacy of Jesus, while Numbers 12:2-7 highlights God''s unique relationship with Moses, affirming his authority over others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 29, 4, 16, 28, 28, 'God spake unto Moses', 'Authority of Divine Communication', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority in both passages. In John 9:29, the speaker acknowledges God''s communication with Moses, while Numbers 16:28 emphasizes Moses'' role as a messenger sent by the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 29, 5, 34, 10, 10, 'we know that God spake unto Moses', 'Connection Between Moses and Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the unique relationship Moses had with God. John 9:29 refers to Moses as a known figure, while Deuteronomy 34:10 highlights that no prophet arose like him, indicating his distinct role.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 29, 11, 22, 27, 27, NULL, 'Connection of Dismissal and Affliction', 'This connection highlights the dismissal of authority in both passages. In John 9:29, the speaker dismisses Jesus as unknown, while in 1 Kings 22:27, the king orders the imprisonment of a prophet, indicating a similar rejection of divine authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
